er\" | \u2014\n| CBS\n| Director<br />15 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Strain (TV series)|The Strain]]''\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| FX\n| Director<br />3 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Under the Dome (TV series)|Under the Dome]]'\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| CBS\n| Director<br />Episode: \"The Red Door\" (2014)<br />Episode: \"But I'm Not\" (2015)\n|-\n| 2015\u20132017\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Last Ship (TV series)|The Last Ship]]''\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014\n| TNT\n| 5 episodes as director<br />Recurring role in season 4\n|-\n| 2015\u20132016\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Tyrant (TV series)|Tyrant]]''\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014\n| FX\n| Director<br />Episode: \"Zanjir\"<br />Episode: \"Bedfellows\"<br />Episode: \"How to Live\"\n|-\n| 2015\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Sleepy Hollow (TV series)|Sleepy Hollow]]''\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014\n| Fox\n| Director<br />Episode: \"I, Witness\"\n|-\n| 2015\u20132016\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Salem (TV series)|Salem]]''\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014\n| WGN America\n| Director<br />Episode: \"The Dark Wine Sea\"<br />Episode: \"Wednesday's Child\"\n|-\n| 2016\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Rush Hour (U.S. TV series)|Rush Hour]]''\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014\n| CBS\n| Director<br />Episode: \"Two Days or The Number of Hours Within the Time Frame\"\n|-\n| 2016\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Outsiders (TV series)|Outsiders]]''\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014\n| WGN America\n| Director<br />Episode: \"Long Live the Bre'lin\"\n|-\n| 2016\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Game of Silence (U.S. TV series)|Game of Silence]]''\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014\n| NBC\n| Director<br />Episode: \"Road Trip\"\n|-\n| 2017\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Shades of Blue (TV series)|Shades of Blue]]''\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014\n| NBC\n| Director<br />Episode: \"Fracture\"<br />Episode: \"House Divided\"\n|-\n| 2018\u20132020\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[MacGyver (2016 TV series)|MacGyver]]''\n| align=\"center\" | Elliot Mason\n| CBS\n| Director \u2014 2 episodes<br>Actor \u2014 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Mr. Mercedes (TV series)|Mr. Mercedes]]''\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014\n| [[Audience (TV network)|Audience]]\n| Director<br />Episode: \"Andale\"\n|-\n| 2018-19\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Mayans MC]]''\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014\n| FX\n| Director<br />Episode: \"Rata/Ch'o\"<br />Episode: \"Tohil\"\n|-\n| 2018-20\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Magnum P.I. (2018 TV series)|Magnum P.I.]]''\n| align=\"center\" | \u2014\n| CBS\n| Director<br />3 episodes\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|693}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|17467}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{amg name|id=75401}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090429205940/http://www.history.com/engineeringanempire History Channel's ''Engineering an Empire'' site]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060702000911/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/story/342880p-292761c.html \"RoboCop in Rome!\"] ''New York Daily News''\n* [https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/15.02/posts.html \"RoboCop, PhD\"] ''Wired News''\n* [http://www.funnyordie.com/videos/521706ecf7/robocop-speaks-to-detroit \"RoboCop speaks to Detroit\"] ''Funny Or Die''\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weller, Peter}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Alamo Heights High School alumni]]\n[[Category:American Academy of Dramatic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American television directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:People from Stevens Point, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Syracuse University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of North Texas alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Peter Weller\n| image        = Peter Weller 2016.jpg\n<!-- NOTE: Do not replace Peter Weller 2016.jpg unless it is with a photo under a public domain or free license (meaning NOT fair use). Any fair use photos (i.e. 'promotional photos') violate the Fair Use Policy and will be deleted. See [[Wikipedia:Fair]] use criteria -->\n| alt          =\n| caption      = Weller at Paradise City Comic Con in 2016\n| birth_name   = Peter Frederick Weller\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1947|6|24}}\n| birth_place  = [[Stevens Point, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| occupation   = {{hlist|Actor|television director|art historian}}<!--Please do not add to this list without first discussing your proposal on the talk page. -->\n| alma mater   = [[University of North Texas]]<small> ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])</small><br>[[Syracuse University]]<small> ([[Master of Arts|M.A.]])</small><br>[[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]<small> ([[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D]])</small>\n| years_active = 1973\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Shari Stowe|2006}}\n| children     = 1 \n}}\n\n'''Peter Frederick Weller''' (born June 24, 1947) is an American film and stage actor, television director, and art historian.\n\nWeller has appeared in more than 70 films and television series, including ''[[RoboCop]]'' (1987) and its sequel ''[[RoboCop 2]]'' (1990), in which he played [[RoboCop (character)|the title character]], ''[[The Adventures of Buckaroo Banzai Across the 8th Dimension]]'' (1984) and ''[[Star Trek Into Darkness]]'' (2013).<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloody-disgusting.com/news/20874|title=TV: 'RoboCop' Heads to Miami for 'Dexter'!}}</ref> He has also appeared in such films as [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Mighty Aphrodite]]'' (1995), the [[Oliver Stone]]-produced ''[[The New Age (film)|The New Age]]'' (1994), and [[David Cronenberg]]'s adaptation of [[William Burroughs]]'s novel ''[[Naked Lunch (film)|Naked Lunch]]'' (1991).\n\nAside from a [[Saturn Award for Best Actor|Saturn Award]] nomination for his ''RoboCop'' role, Weller received an [[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film|Academy Award]] nomination for his 1993 short ''Partners,'' in which he also acted. In [[television]], he hosted the program ''[[Engineering an Empire]]'' on the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]] from 2005 to 2007. He also played [[List of minor characters in 24#Christopher Henderson|Christopher Henderson]] in the [[24 (season 5)|fifth season]] of ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]'',  [[List of Dexter characters#Stan Liddy|Stan Liddy]] in the [[Dexter (season 5)|fifth season]] of the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] original series ''[[Dexter (TV series)|Dexter]]'', as well as [[List of Sons of Anarchy characters#Charles 'Charlie' Barosky|Charles \"Charlie\" Barosky]] in 11 episodes in  [[Sons of Anarchy (season 6)|(Season 6)]] of [[Kurt Sutter]] 's long running  ''[[Sons of Anarchy]]''. Since 2012, Weller has been involved in the [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] (now [[Netflix]]) series ''[[Longmire (TV series)|Longmire]]'' both as a director and an actor. In 2017, Weller appeared on ''[[The Last Ship (TV series)|The Last Ship]]'' as Dr. Paul Vellek.\n\n==Early life==\nWeller was born June 24, 1947, in [[Stevens Point, Wisconsin]], the son of Dorothy Jean (n\u00e9e Davidson), a homemaker, and Frederick Bradford Weller, a lawyer, federal judge, and career helicopter pilot for the [[United States Army]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/28/Peter-Weller.html |title=Peter Weller Biography (1947\u2013) |publisher=Filmreference.com |date=1947-06-24 |accessdate=2010-10-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgazette.com/obits/2002/dec02/weller12-3.htm |title=Obituaries |publisher=pcgazette.com |date= |accessdate=2010-10-07 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030320163927/http://www.pcgazette.com/obits/2002/dec02/weller12-3.htm |archivedate=2003-03-20}}</ref> Weller had a \"middle-class [[Catholic]]\" upbringing.<ref name=\"cigaraficionado.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cigaraficionado.com/Cigar/CA_Profiles/People_Profile/0,2540,254,00.html |title=People Profile &#124; Peter Weller |publisher=Cigar Aficionado |date=1996-03-01 |accessdate=2010-10-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701193300/http://www.cigaraficionado.com/Cigar/CA_Profiles/People_Profile/0,2540,254,00.html# |archive-date=2010-07-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref> As a result of his father's army work, Weller spent many years abroad during his childhood. His family lived in [[Germany]] for several years before eventually moving to [[Texas]], where he attended [[Alamo Heights High School]] in [[San Antonio]].\n\n==Education==\nWhile enrolled at North Texas State University (now the [[University of North Texas]]), he played [[trumpet]] in one of the campus bands. He graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in Theatre<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unt.edu/emeraldeaglehonors/honorees.htm |title=2014 Emerald Eagle Honors Honorees |work=University of North Texas |accessdate=February 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222135727/http://www.unt.edu/emeraldeaglehonors/honorees.htm |archivedate=February 22, 2014 }}</ref> and began his acting career after attending the [[American Academy of Dramatic Arts]].{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\nIn 2004, Weller completed a [[Master of Arts]] degree in [[Roman Renaissance|Roman and Renaissance Art]] at [[Syracuse University]], and occasionally taught courses in [[ancient history]] at the university.\n\nIn 2007, Weller began a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] at [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]], in [[Italian Renaissance#Culture|Italian Renaissance Art History]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.theflorentine.net/articles/article-view.asp?issuetocId=2576 |title=An interview with Peter Weller |publisher=Theflorentine.net |date=2007-10-18 |accessdate=2010-10-07}}</ref>  In October 2013 he filed his dissertation,<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vulture.com/2013/05/peter-weller-star-trek-into-darkness-interview.html | title = Peter Weller on Star Trek, Getting His Ph.D., and Defending J.J. Abrams | accessdate = 2013-08-21 | last = Ebiri | first = Bilge | date = 20 May 2013 | work = vulture.com | quote = When is your dissertation due? 'I file it in October.'}}</ref> entitled ''\"[http://escholarship.org/uc/item/0dm859tj Alberti Before Florence: Early Sources Informing Leon Battista Alberti\u2019s De pictura]\"'', and was awarded his doctorate in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arthistory.ucla.edu/alumni-phd-recipients/|title=Ph.D. Recipients|date=2014|accessdate=2016-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url= http://trekmovie.com/2014/08/03/pegg-scotty-not-a-clown-talks-star-trek-2016-peter-weller-marcus-not-villain | title= STLV: Pegg: Scotty Not A \u2018Clown\u2019 \u2013 Talks Accent & Star Trek 2016 + Weller: Marcus Not \u2018Villain\u2019 + more | work = TrekMovie.com | date = 3 August 2014 | quote = Yes you read that sentence right: Dr. Peter Weller, who recently completed a PhD in Italian history. And he didn\u2019t let you forget it, including correcting one fan who addressed him as \u201cMister Weller.\u201d}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Stage===\nWeller's stage career began in the 1970s with appearances on Broadway in ''Full Circle'', directed by [[Otto Preminger]], and ''[[Summer Brave]]'', [[William Inge]]'s rewrite of his play ''Picnic''. About this time, he became a member of the famed [[Actors Studio]].<ref>[https://movies.nytimes.com/person/531156/Peter-Weller \"Movies & TV: Peter Weller\"]. ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved May 9, 2012.</ref>\n\nIn December 2006, Weller starred as architect [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] at Chicago's [[Goodman Theatre]] in ''Frank's Home'', a new play by [[Richard Nelson (playwright)|Richard Nelson]].\n\n===Film===\nWeller appeared in the 1984 film ''[[Firstborn (1984 film)|Firstborn]]'' with [[Christopher Collet]], where he played the abusive boyfriend of Collet's mother (played by [[Teri Garr]]).\n\nWeller has appeared in more than 50 films and television series, including turns as the title characters in ''[[The Adventures of Buckaroo Banzai Across the 8th Dimension]]'', and blockbuster hits ''[[RoboCop]]'' and ''[[RoboCop 2]]'',<ref name=\"auto\"/> he portrayed Starfleet Admiral Alexander Marcus in ''[[Star Trek Into Darkness]]'' in 2013. He has also appeared in such critically acclaimed films as [[Woody Allen]]'s ''[[Mighty Aphrodite]]'', the [[Oliver Stone]]-produced ''[[The New Age (film)|The New Age]]'' and [[David Cronenberg]]'s movie of [[William Burroughs]]'s novel ''[[Naked Lunch (film)|Naked Lunch]]''.\n\nIn 1995, he appeared in ''[[Screamers (1995 film)|Screamers]]'', a science-fiction film based on the short story \"[[Second Variety]]\" by [[Philip K. Dick]] and directed by [[Christian Duguay (director)|Christian Duguay]].\n\n===Television===\nIn a 1977 episode of the television series ''[[Lou Grant (TV series)|Lou Grant]]'', he played [[Oberster SA-F\u00fchrer]] Donald Sterner/Stryker, a tragically disillusioned [[Jewish-American]] [[Neo-Nazi]] leader who later committed suicide off screen with his [[1911 pistol|Colt .45]] near the end of the episode when his heritage was discovered.\n\nOn television, he played the shuttle captain in the short-lived series ''[[Odyssey 5]]'' and made guest appearances as [[Earthling|Terran]] supremacist John Frederick Paxton in the ''[[Star Trek: Enterprise]]'' episodes \"[[Demons (Star Trek: Enterprise)|Demons]]\", \"[[Terra Prime]]\" and in ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]'' as the character Alistair Peck.\n\nWeller was a contributor to the [[History (U.S. TV channel)|History Channel]] in several productions, credited as \"Peter Weller, [[Syracuse University]]\", where he was an adjunct faculty member. He was later a graduate student in art history at [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]], focusing on the [[Italian Renaissance]].\n\nIn 2005, Weller co-starred as the Captain in a made-for-television remake of ''[[The Poseidon Adventure (2005 film)|The Poseidon Adventure]]''.\n\n[[File:Peter Weller (cropped).jpg|thumb|Weller at the Texas Theater in Dallas, Texas, in 2012]]\n\nIn 2006, Weller joined the cast of ''[[24 (TV series)|24]]'' as terrorist collaborator Christopher Henderson.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2010/07/peter-weller-joins-showtimes-dexter|title=Peter Weller Joins Showtime's 'Dexter'}}</ref> Weller received a \"cheer\" in ''[[TV Guide]]'''s \"Cheers & Jeers\" section for his performance.\n\nOn January 15, 2010, Weller was seen in a teaser trailer for the companion documentary ''God of War: Unearthing the Legend'' that was featured in the game ''[[God of War III]]'' which Weller also hosted.<ref name=\"destructoid.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/awesome-robocop-to-host-god-of-war-documentary-160945.phtml|title=Awesome: RoboCop to Host God of War Documentary|first=Nick|last=Chester}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2010, Weller guest-starred in an episode of the science fiction drama ''[[Fringe (TV series)|Fringe]]''. He also guest-starred on the [[Showtime (TV channel)|Showtime]] original series ''[[Dexter (TV series)|Dexter]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/38494/peter-weller-joins-showtimes-dexter|title=Peter Weller Joins Showtime's Dexter}}</ref> and had a guest appearance in the December 22, 2010 episode of ''[[Psych]]'' where he played villain \"Yin\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvsquad.com/2010/12/23/psych-season-finale-recap-who-was-yin |title='Psych' Season Finale Recap: Who Was Yin?}}</ref>\n\nSince 2012, he is appearing in a recurring role as Lucien Connally on the crime drama television series ''[[Longmire (TV series)|Longmire]]''.\n\nIn 2013, he played the part of the villain in the remake of the \"Hookman\" episode of the original ''[[Hawaii Five-O (1968 TV series)|Hawaii Five-O]]''. The part was originally played in 1973 by [[J. J. Armes]]. In seasons six and seven of ''[[Sons of Anarchy]]'', he plays the ruthless ex-cop Charles Barosky, a boss at the Stockton port and has dealings with the SAMCRO motorcycle club.\n\nIn 2017, Weller began appearing as Dr. Paul Vellek, a scientist, on ''[[The Last Ship (TV series)|The Last Ship]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/the-last-ship-peter-weller-tom-fight/|title=The Last Ship Exclusive: Peter Weller Gets Tom Ready to Fight|date=25 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Directing===\nWeller has also directed various projects for television, including episodes of ''[[Homicide: Life on the Street]]'', ''[[Monk (TV series)|Monk]]'' and three episodes of the aforementioned ''Odyssey 5''. He directed a 1997 adaptation of [[Elmore Leonard]]'s ''Gold Coast'' starring [[David Caruso]] and [[Marg Helgenberger]] after previously starring in a version of Leonard's thriller ''[[Cat Chaser]]''. He has directed eleven episodes of the series ''[[Sons of Anarchy]]'', two in Season 4, titled \"Dorylus\" (air date 9/20/11) and  \"Hands\", three in Season 5, titled \"Authority Vested\", \"Toad's Wild Ride\" and \"Darthy\", three in Season 6, titled \"One One Six\", \"Los Fantasmas\" and \"Aon Rud Pearsanta\" and three in Season 7, titled \"Some Strange Eruption\", \"What a Piece of Work Is Man\" and \"Suits of Woe\". He has directed one episode each season of ''Longmire'' since 2012. Most recently in 2018, Weller has directed episode 4 of the revamped CBS drama, \u201cMagnum PI\u201d.\n\n===Voice acting===\nWeller voiced the character of [[Batman|Bruce Wayne]] in the two-part 2013 [[Batman: The Dark Knight Returns (film)|animated adaptation]] of ''[[The Dark Knight Returns]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.batman-on-film.com/animated-films_TDKReturns_cast-announced_5-23-12.html|title=Animated THE DARK KNIGHT RETURNS Cast Announced}}</ref> and the titular character in the video game ''[[Wilson's Heart (video game)|Wilson's Heart]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/27/15070102/wilsons-heart-oculus-rift-game-preview-release-date-pricing|title=Wilson\u2019s Heart is a bold VR mash-up of game styles and film genres|publisher=}} In 2019 he returned to voice Robocop in a series of commercials for KFC.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn June 24, 2006, on his 59th birthday, Weller married his longtime girlfriend, actress Shari Stowe, at the Santa Maria Assunta church in [[Positano]], [[Italy]].  Among the guests attending the wedding were [[Carrie Fisher]] and [[Marg Helgenberger]].<ref>{{cite news |title='Robocop' Star Weds in Italy |url=http://www.zap2it.com/movies/zap-peterwellermarried,0,5482264.story |work=Zap2It |date=June 29, 2006 |accessdate=February 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n*(1988) [[Saturn Award for Best Actor]] \u2013 ''[[RoboCop]]''\n*(1992) [[Genie Award for Best Performance by an Actor in a Leading Role]] \u2013 ''[[Naked Lunch (film)|Naked Lunch]]''\n*(1994) [[Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film]] \u2013 ''Partners''- ''Nominated''\n*(2002) [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Supporting Male]]  \u2013 ''[[Ivans XTC]]''\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Title\n!width=103 scope=\"col\" | Role\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1979\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Butch and Sundance: The Early Days]]''\n| Joe Le Fors\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Just Tell Me What You Want]]''\n| Steven Routledge\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Shoot the Moon]]''\n| Frank Henderson\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Of Unknown Origin]]''\n| Bart Hughes\n| Paris Film Festival for Best Actor\n|-\n| 1984\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[The Adventures of Buckaroo Banzai Across the 8th Dimension]]''\n| Buckaroo Banzai\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Firstborn (1984 film)|Firstborn]]''\n| Sam\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[A Killing Affair (1986 film)|A Killing Affair]]''\n| Baston Morris\n|\n|-\n| 198